    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "that sounds a bit complicated lol. can you just explain the actual mechanics of it? like who actually holds the money and what happens if the seller doesn't show up or something?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Certainly! In the enchanted realm of real estate, the escrow is like a magical chest, guarded by a neutral party, often a bank or a professional escrow company. This chest holds the treasure, or in your case, the money for the house purchase. The escrow agent is the keeper of this chest, ensuring that neither you nor the seller can access the treasure until the agreed-upon conditions are met.\n\nNow, if the seller, our elusive dragon, doesn't show up to the closing ceremony, the escrow agent will hold onto the treasure until the dragon agrees to leave the castle. If the dragon refuses to budge, the escrow agent will release the treasure to you, the knight, as compensation for the broken promise. But if the dragon does show up and the castle is yours, the escrow agent will then release the treasure to the seller, allowing them to claim their share of the spoils.\n\nIn this way, the escrow agent ensures that the treasure is only released when both parties have fulfilled their promises, keeping the peace in the kingdom of Toronto. It's a bit like a magical contract, with the escrow agent as the guardian of the agreement. And remember, if the dragon refuses to leave, you might just find yourself with a new, unexpected",
      "source": "target",
